1
00:01:09,540 --> 00:01:11,190
Turn around. Hands up!

2
00:01:12,823 --> 00:01:14,116
- [GUNSHOT]
- [SCREAMS]

3
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:30,590
[SCOFFS] Well, well.

4
00:01:32,140 --> 00:01:33,802
Just as I suspected.

5
00:01:34,640 --> 00:01:36,840
Kind of obvious when
you think about it, huh?

6
00:01:37,460 --> 00:01:40,800
[PUERTO RICAN ACCENT] No for
me, boss. I no see that coming.

7
00:01:40,893 --> 00:01:44,145
Anyone with an alibi is always
a suspect, Markowitz.

8
00:01:44,146 --> 00:01:46,982
How do you know these
things, jefe? [CHUCKLES]

9
00:01:53,340 --> 00:01:55,740
[NORMAL VOICE] Wait. I'm the sidekick?

10
00:01:55,824 --> 00:01:58,201
Yes. You're the sidekick.

11
00:01:58,202 --> 00:02:01,205
[CHUCKLES] Thank you so much.
I... I don't know what to say.

12
00:02:01,206 --> 00:02:02,940
You're welcome. [CHUCKLES]

13
00:02:02,960 --> 00:02:04,875
Now, should we go back to the top?

14
00:02:05,876 --> 00:02:07,211
Yeah? Okay.

15
00:02:07,740 --> 00:02:09,460
Well, well.

16
00:02:09,500 --> 00:02:11,215
Just as I suspected.

17
00:02:11,680 --> 00:02:13,000
Kind of obvious when...

18
00:02:13,020 --> 00:02:14,510
Why the accents?

19
00:02:14,593 --> 00:02:16,136
You're Puerto Rican.

20
00:02:16,220 --> 00:02:17,471
Uh... [SPEAKS SPANISH]

21
00:02:17,554 --> 00:02:19,848
Hey. [CHUCKLES] Not bad.

22
00:02:19,932 --> 00:02:22,267
There you go. [CHUCKLES] Okay.

23
00:02:22,351 --> 00:02:23,685
[INHALES SHARPLY]

24
00:02:23,700 --> 00:02:24,770
Well, well.

25
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:27,060
Just as I suspected.

26
00:02:27,540 --> 00:02:30,980
He watched the light fade
from the man's eyes,

27
00:02:31,960 --> 00:02:35,610
the withdrawing of the
life-force from the body

28
00:02:35,620 --> 00:02:38,534
seeming to coincide

29
00:02:39,120 --> 00:02:43,200
with the evacuation of his bowels
into his gabardine slacks.

30
00:02:43,220 --> 00:02:45,640
"... into his gabardine slacks."

31
00:02:46,260 --> 00:02:47,680
Before long...

32
00:02:47,860 --> 00:02:49,040
"Before long... "

33
00:02:49,127 --> 00:02:52,840
- ... the putrid scent of feces...
- "... the putrid scent of feces... "

34
00:02:52,880 --> 00:02:54,424
... hung in the air like...

35
00:02:55,551 --> 00:02:57,511
the ghost of a dead lover.

36
00:02:57,520 --> 00:03:01,580
"... hung in the air like the
ghost of a dead lover."

37
00:03:01,600 --> 00:03:02,808
You getting this, Marty?

38
00:03:02,891 --> 00:03:05,936
You know, you gotta keep up
with the rhythm of the prose.

39
00:03:06,019 --> 00:03:07,271
You know, it's like jazz.

40
00:03:07,896 --> 00:03:09,355
- Uh-huh. Yeah, yeah. Yeah.
- Yeah?

41
00:03:09,356 --> 00:03:11,358
[MARTY] I got it. I got it. Got it.

42
00:03:13,400 --> 00:03:17,110
"Another day, another dollar,"
as he always said.

43
00:03:17,197 --> 00:03:19,408
"... another dollar... "

44
00:03:19,420 --> 00:03:21,618
He turned on his heel and walked out.

45
00:03:21,702 --> 00:03:22,828
Another day,

46
00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:27,120
- another case closed.
- "Another day... Case closed."

47
00:03:28,480 --> 00:03:29,620
The end.

48
00:03:30,400 --> 00:03:31,460
"The end."

49
00:03:31,800 --> 00:03:32,960
Or is it?

50
00:03:34,480 --> 00:03:35,630
Isn't it?

51
00:03:37,180 --> 00:03:38,800
Just saying that, um,

52
00:03:39,840 --> 00:03:42,800
maybe Dr. Kessler isn't
as dead as he seemed.

53
00:03:43,740 --> 00:03:46,100
- Oh, wow. [CHUCKLES] No way.
- Hmm.

54
00:03:46,185 --> 00:03:47,686
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

55
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:49,490
- [MARTY] I love it.
- Well, there we go.

56
00:03:49,521 --> 00:03:50,522
[MARTY] Ah.

57
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:54,350
Book nine of the "Some
Like It" series complete.

58
00:03:54,380 --> 00:03:56,778
[STRAINS] Ah. Incredible.

59
00:03:57,280 --> 00:03:59,573
And... [STAMMERS] ship all
of this to the publisher?

60
00:03:59,590 --> 00:04:02,201
I think so, yeah. I think it
reads better as a series.

61
00:04:02,220 --> 00:04:05,204
But it's this last book that's gonna
really get them interested.

62
00:04:05,287 --> 00:04:06,847
- Yeah.
- It's the ultimate page-turner.

63
00:04:07,200 --> 00:04:09,700
Bottom line, though, it's gonna sell.

64
00:04:09,720 --> 00:04:12,461
And at the end of the day, that's
all the publishers care about.

65
00:04:12,480 --> 00:04:13,980
Getting noses in books.

66
00:04:14,340 --> 00:04:16,630
[STRAINING] Ouch.

67
00:04:16,650 --> 00:04:19,718
Whew. My stomach kinda
hurts when I do that.

68
00:04:19,801 --> 00:04:22,094
Yeah, well, you know what? My
head really hurts when I do this.

69
00:04:22,095 --> 00:04:23,597
I just wrote an entire novel.

70
00:04:23,620 --> 00:04:25,804
But this has been going on
for a couple of weeks now.

71
00:04:25,805 --> 00:04:28,080
Well, uh, maybe your
stomach problems are back.

72
00:04:28,110 --> 00:04:30,479
[STAMMERS] It... It feels different.

73
00:04:30,920 --> 00:04:33,890
It sounds weird, but I
can't fart, you know?

74
00:04:33,920 --> 00:04:35,567
Even though it feels like I need to.

75
00:04:36,310 --> 00:04:39,446
And then if I cough, it feels
like I might, you know, poop

76
00:04:39,450 --> 00:04:41,180
- by mistake.
- Okay. Yeah.

77
00:04:41,210 --> 00:04:44,493
That's too much information. Thank you.

78
00:04:52,880 --> 00:04:54,040
[SIGHS]

79
00:04:55,980 --> 00:04:57,170
[EXHALES]

80
00:04:57,810 --> 00:05:01,740
- Synced & corrected by<font color="#E83286"> MementMori </font>-
-- <font color="#138CE9">www.addic7ed.com</font> --

81
00:05:15,220 --> 00:05:18,399
- [STRAINS, SIGHS]
- Marty, are you okay?

82
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:22,363
[SIGHS] I just have a little bit
of discomfort when I move.

83
00:05:22,364 --> 00:05:23,949
Or... Or don't move.

84
00:05:24,720 --> 00:05:25,900
Or breathe.

85
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:29,246
That doesn't sound so good.
Sit down. I'll get you some water.

86
00:05:29,270 --> 00:05:31,331
No. No, no, no. I...
I can't. We're too busy.

87
00:05:31,370 --> 00:05:33,542
You weren't too busy
to have a heart attack.

88
00:05:33,570 --> 00:05:35,002
You... You scared us once before.

89
00:05:35,010 --> 00:05:37,254
You think I'm gonna let
you do that again? Sit.

90
00:05:38,797 --> 00:05:40,883
[SIGHS, EXHALES SHARPLY]

91
00:05:40,966 --> 00:05:44,520
Hey, uh, listen. I... I know this
probably isn't the, uh, best time,

92
00:05:44,540 --> 00:05:46,763
but I was wondering if I
could get a word with you

93
00:05:46,770 --> 00:05:50,299
about, uh, some financial, uh, stuff.

94
00:05:50,300 --> 00:05:52,100
Oh, B... Uh, Bruce, can...

95
00:05:52,120 --> 00:05:54,478
can you just email
Norman Horowitz about it?

96
00:05:54,479 --> 00:05:56,315
Um... [STAMMERS]
Well, it's kinda urgent.

97
00:05:56,330 --> 00:05:58,360
And I figured it's easier to talk to you

98
00:05:58,380 --> 00:06:00,040
because... [CHUCKLES] you're right here.

99
00:06:00,060 --> 00:06:01,195
What's up, Bruce?

100
00:06:02,154 --> 00:06:05,449
Uh, oh, I-I... I was just, uh...

101
00:06:06,700 --> 00:06:08,243
That's okay. We can talk later.

102
00:06:09,286 --> 00:06:10,370
Problem?

103
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:15,040
[STAMMERS] No, no.
[CHUCKLES] No problem.

104
00:06:15,125 --> 00:06:18,470
Hmm. It kind of sounds like there is.

105
00:06:18,500 --> 00:06:21,590
[STUTTERS] Come on, Bruce.
You can say anything.

106
00:06:23,780 --> 00:06:26,760
I was having a look at
this year's accounts

107
00:06:26,780 --> 00:06:29,097
on top of this year's
expenses, and, uh...

108
00:06:31,700 --> 00:06:32,851
we have a big problem.

109
00:06:32,852 --> 00:06:35,320
We don't use the word "problem" at AFC.

110
00:06:35,340 --> 00:06:36,644
We use the word "solution."

111
00:06:36,645 --> 00:06:39,180
Yeah, but sometimes you
need to know the problem

112
00:06:39,200 --> 00:06:40,651
in order to find the solution.

113
00:06:40,670 --> 00:06:42,611
Okay, thank you, Cathy.
That'll be enough.

114
00:06:42,620 --> 00:06:46,740
Our problem is that profits are
down and midtown rents are up.

115
00:06:47,282 --> 00:06:49,722
- Yeah. We can't afford the lease here.
- Okay, you know what?

116
00:06:49,740 --> 00:06:51,661
This sounds like something
for Norman Horowitz.

117
00:06:51,662 --> 00:06:53,740
Yeah. I gotta be honest.
It's killing us. Right?

118
00:06:53,750 --> 00:06:56,542
Another six months of this rent,
we go under. Simple as that.

119
00:06:56,570 --> 00:06:58,918
All right, you know what?
All I hear is the word "problem."

120
00:06:58,919 --> 00:07:00,420
But he has a solution.

121
00:07:00,470 --> 00:07:04,049
Okay. Well, lead with
that next time, please.

122
00:07:04,050 --> 00:07:06,770
A contact of mine tipped me off
that the Lea & Perrins factory

123
00:07:06,802 --> 00:07:08,887
in Fair Lawn, New Jersey is empty.

124
00:07:08,920 --> 00:07:10,211
Now, we could move out of here,

125
00:07:10,230 --> 00:07:12,500
rent that place for, like,
under half the price.

126
00:07:12,520 --> 00:07:14,685
It's twice the size, but
we'd have to move quick.

127
00:07:14,700 --> 00:07:16,979
- That place is gonna go fast.
- No. [CHUCKLES]

128
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:19,231
Forget it, Bruce. We're not
moving to New Jersey.

129
00:07:19,940 --> 00:07:21,400
This is a great opportunity.

130
00:07:21,483 --> 00:07:25,611
You know, when I, uh, encouraged
more feedback from the workforce,

131
00:07:25,612 --> 00:07:28,740
I was expecting suggestions
more along the lines of, uh,

132
00:07:28,760 --> 00:07:30,959
"Could we get some non-dairy
creamer for the coffee cart?"

133
00:07:30,960 --> 00:07:32,243
Not, "Hey, I've got an idea.

134
00:07:32,244 --> 00:07:34,245
Why don't we tank our business
and move to New Jersey?"

135
00:07:34,246 --> 00:07:36,248
But the problem is that we can't...

136
00:07:36,250 --> 00:07:38,208
You don't take AFC out of Manhattan.

137
00:07:38,230 --> 00:07:40,168
It's classy. It's classic.

138
00:07:40,169 --> 00:07:43,213
New Jersey is second-rate. It's cheap.

139
00:07:43,290 --> 00:07:45,520
Do you think that the
pastrami from Katz's Deli

140
00:07:45,540 --> 00:07:46,716
tastes the same in New Jersey?

141
00:07:46,717 --> 00:07:49,678
- Yes.
- I think that it probably would, yeah.

142
00:07:49,680 --> 00:07:51,972
[IMITATES BUZZER]
No, incorrect. It doesn't.

143
00:07:51,990 --> 00:07:57,059
Uh, moving, in itself,
Bruce, is expensive. So...

144
00:07:57,060 --> 00:08:00,184
[IKE] Look, Bruce, business
is all about perception.

145
00:08:00,185 --> 00:08:01,650
If we were to pack up

146
00:08:01,670 --> 00:08:04,180
and move out to some sauce
factory in New Jersey

147
00:08:04,200 --> 00:08:06,861
with our schmekel between our
legs, that sends a message.

148
00:08:06,862 --> 00:08:10,370
It sends a message to our customers
as well as our competition.

149
00:08:10,390 --> 00:08:13,951
And that message is, "Hey,
look at us. We're losers."

150
00:08:13,952 --> 00:08:15,912
Now, you wanna make a suggestion?

151
00:08:15,913 --> 00:08:18,873
Maybe we should try moving to
a place that's more expensive.

152
00:08:18,874 --> 00:08:20,417
That would be smart.

153
00:08:20,420 --> 00:08:22,880
Now, if all of you financial
wizards would excuse me,

154
00:08:22,900 --> 00:08:24,338
I have patients to see.

155
00:08:24,760 --> 00:08:27,049
Thankfully, none of them
are as crazy as Bruce.

156
00:08:27,591 --> 00:08:29,850
[SIGHS, SCOFFS]

157
00:08:29,870 --> 00:08:31,929
Here. Take that.

158
00:08:33,360 --> 00:08:37,180
Listen, I... I don't wanna
cause any trouble, all right?

159
00:08:37,200 --> 00:08:39,061
But this is a serious situation.

160
00:08:39,940 --> 00:08:42,140
You know I care about
this company, Marty.

161
00:08:42,170 --> 00:08:45,360
I was there when your dad put his
sweat and blood into this place.

162
00:08:45,380 --> 00:08:47,736
I feel like I sorta owe it
to him to keep it alive.

163
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:50,140
[STUTTERS] I don't know.

164
00:08:50,170 --> 00:08:53,140
I... I mean, I hear what you're
saying, Bruce, but... [SIGHS]

165
00:08:53,160 --> 00:08:54,659
I think we gotta listen to the experts.

166
00:08:54,660 --> 00:08:56,880
You know, it's... it's his world.

167
00:08:56,910 --> 00:08:58,455
He knows what he's talking about.

168
00:08:58,470 --> 00:08:59,914
- [SIGHS]
- [INHALES SHARPLY, GROANS]

169
00:08:59,915 --> 00:09:03,042
- It's... Jesus. See a fricking doctor.
- No.

170
00:09:03,043 --> 00:09:05,587
No, no. A doctor's only
gonna make things worse.

171
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:06,860
It's like taking your car in.

172
00:09:06,880 --> 00:09:08,480
They're gonna find something eventually.

173
00:09:08,490 --> 00:09:10,675
That is it. I'm making the call.

174
00:09:10,676 --> 00:09:13,637
- No.
- You are not crapping out on me, Marty.

175
00:09:13,650 --> 00:09:17,850
I am not springing for a new dress
for a perfectly avoidable funeral.

176
00:09:20,700 --> 00:09:21,853
You have a hernia.

177
00:09:21,870 --> 00:09:24,021
You will need surgery
to repair the tear.

178
00:09:24,022 --> 00:09:27,483
Surgery? Like surgery-surgery?

179
00:09:27,484 --> 00:09:30,112
I'm afraid so, and as soon as possible.

180
00:09:30,130 --> 00:09:32,410
Uh, good news is it's a
straightforward procedure

181
00:09:32,430 --> 00:09:33,573
and nothing to worry about.

182
00:09:33,574 --> 00:09:35,242
Oh, well, I guess that is good news.

183
00:09:35,270 --> 00:09:38,050
So... [STAMMERS] in and out?
You know, like, same day?

184
00:09:38,070 --> 00:09:40,247
Not quite. We get in there pretty deep.

185
00:09:40,270 --> 00:09:42,639
We keep you around to make sure
the sutures don't get infected.

186
00:09:42,640 --> 00:09:44,042
Sutures?

187
00:09:44,070 --> 00:09:45,377
[DOCTOR] You won't feel them.

188
00:09:45,390 --> 00:09:47,838
You'll wake up very comfortable
from the anesthesia.

189
00:09:48,680 --> 00:09:52,300
Anesthesia? What? Hold on.
This doesn't sound so simple.

190
00:09:52,384 --> 00:09:56,430
Uh, um, how long will
I be in the hospital?

191
00:09:56,513 --> 00:09:59,057
I have a lot of responsibilities
I need to take care of.

192
00:09:59,141 --> 00:10:00,558
What sort of responsibilities?

193
00:10:00,559 --> 00:10:03,603
Well, you know, I... [STAMMERS]
My... My constituents.

194
00:10:03,604 --> 00:10:04,813
They're counting on me.

195
00:10:04,820 --> 00:10:06,523
Ah, you're an elected official?

196
00:10:06,540 --> 00:10:10,939
No, I... [SIGHS] I don't think
I used that word correctly.

197
00:10:10,940 --> 00:10:13,447
[STAMMERS] People need
me to be healthy, is all.

198
00:10:13,470 --> 00:10:15,824
Not long at all. Should
only be a few days.

199
00:10:15,850 --> 00:10:18,911
And then, obviously, there
will be a period of recovery.

200
00:10:18,994 --> 00:10:21,330
A period of recovery?

201
00:10:22,460 --> 00:10:23,910
Oh, my God.

202
00:10:24,600 --> 00:10:27,160
All right, well... [SIGHS]
I guess I will, uh...

203
00:10:27,740 --> 00:10:29,790
I have to get my affairs in order.

204
00:10:29,820 --> 00:10:33,884
Mr. Markowitz, I assure you,
it's really pretty routine.

205
00:10:33,900 --> 00:10:36,386
We'll get everything popped
back in, and then off you go.

206
00:10:36,400 --> 00:10:37,620
[EXHALES]

207
00:10:38,060 --> 00:10:40,010
Right. Okay.

208
00:10:41,320 --> 00:10:43,050
I've been thinking, Marty.

209
00:10:43,073 --> 00:10:46,270
That whole thing with Bruce
didn't sit well with me.

210
00:10:46,271 --> 00:10:48,106
The Bruce thing? What... What thing?

211
00:10:50,140 --> 00:10:51,360
[GRUNTS]

212
00:10:51,380 --> 00:10:52,860
A move to Jersey.

213
00:10:52,861 --> 00:10:55,279
- Oh.
- I just don't have time for negativity.

214
00:10:55,280 --> 00:10:57,115
It's toxic.

215
00:10:57,130 --> 00:10:58,951
And it's not good for your anxiety.

216
00:11:00,660 --> 00:11:03,120
- I don't know. I... I just think...
- Oh.

217
00:11:03,205 --> 00:11:04,206
You know what?

218
00:11:05,180 --> 00:11:06,830
We're out of time for today.

219
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:09,669
- Oh, right.
- Yeah.

220
00:11:10,380 --> 00:11:13,714
Uh... So, uh, with the koi.

221
00:11:13,715 --> 00:11:17,880
They have this ich parasite
problem with their gills currently,

222
00:11:17,900 --> 00:11:21,430
so they're gonna need a... a
little more care than usual.

223
00:11:21,515 --> 00:11:24,600
Uh, can I ask you to put some
formalin drops in the pond

224
00:11:24,601 --> 00:11:25,940
as soon as you get down there

225
00:11:25,960 --> 00:11:27,225
- for the weekend?
- Sure.

226
00:11:27,226 --> 00:11:28,680
- Yeah.
- Ah, great.

227
00:11:28,700 --> 00:11:30,774
Uh, about the feeding schedule.

228
00:11:30,850 --> 00:11:33,360
I... I think the long-release
block should be good

229
00:11:33,380 --> 00:11:34,736
for a few more days,

230
00:11:34,820 --> 00:11:37,114
but you may wanna add
a precise measured pour

231
00:11:37,197 --> 00:11:40,241
of the spirulina algae
as a weekend treat.

232
00:11:40,242 --> 00:11:42,785
Think of it as their
Saturday morning pancakes.

233
00:11:42,786 --> 00:11:44,955
- Hah.
- It's all labeled in the guest house.

234
00:11:44,970 --> 00:11:46,539
And also, I wrote it down.

235
00:11:46,540 --> 00:11:47,541
Got it.

236
00:11:49,540 --> 00:11:54,960
Oh, and, um, if I... If
I don't make it, uh...

237
00:11:55,780 --> 00:11:59,510
can you just, uh, promise
me they'll be taken care of?

238
00:11:59,540 --> 00:12:01,580
Seriously? Come on.

239
00:12:01,600 --> 00:12:04,975
Look, let's not make a
huge deal of this, okay?

240
00:12:04,980 --> 00:12:07,740
It's a hernia. Yeah? It's
like getting your tonsils out.

241
00:12:07,760 --> 00:12:09,839
The girls got their tonsils
out when they were little,

242
00:12:09,840 --> 00:12:11,350
and it was fine.

243
00:12:11,380 --> 00:12:14,358
You know, we watched <i>Jungle Book</i>
and we ate ice cream and Jell-O.

244
00:12:14,359 --> 00:12:16,442
You're gonna be great.
You're in very good hands.

245
00:12:16,443 --> 00:12:18,220
And your fish are in good hands too.

246
00:12:18,620 --> 00:12:21,490
I know how much they mean to you,
so they mean just as much to me.

247
00:12:21,575 --> 00:12:23,744
Aw, I appreciate that.

248
00:12:23,827 --> 00:12:26,246
- [CHUCKLES] Come here.
- [CHUCKLES]

249
00:12:27,900 --> 00:12:30,200
Is that a hernia or are you
just pleased to see me?

250
00:12:30,220 --> 00:12:32,127
- Ah!
- [CHUCKLES]

251
00:12:32,150 --> 00:12:33,212
Come on.

252
00:12:33,879 --> 00:12:35,390
- [CHUCKLES]
- I love playing around.

253
00:12:35,422 --> 00:12:38,634
- Oh. Ah, all right.
- Okay.

254
00:12:39,420 --> 00:12:40,630
Talk soon.

255
00:12:42,980 --> 00:12:45,130
[MALE NURSE] <i>Finally, we
just need contact details</i>

256
00:12:45,140 --> 00:12:46,300
<i>for your next of kin.</i>

257
00:12:46,391 --> 00:12:49,100
Just a formality, in case of emergency.

258
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:53,148
Parents? Wife? Children?
Siblings? Could be anyone.

259
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:55,400
Um... [SIGHS]

260
00:12:56,600 --> 00:12:58,770
Ike Herschkopf.

261
00:12:59,200 --> 00:13:04,400
H-E-R-S-C-H-K-O-P-F.

262
00:13:04,760 --> 00:13:06,780
Great. Good luck.

263
00:13:27,307 --> 00:13:30,060
[BREATHES SHAKILY]

264
00:14:02,060 --> 00:14:03,920
You did great, Marty.

265
00:14:05,679 --> 00:14:08,682
[MACHINERY BEEPING]

266
00:14:10,880 --> 00:14:12,810
It's okay. You're in recovery.

267
00:14:13,620 --> 00:14:14,810
Oh.

268
00:14:17,360 --> 00:14:18,730
Okay.

269
00:14:38,100 --> 00:14:39,370
[DOOR OPENS]

270
00:14:40,172 --> 00:14:42,424
Doctor ordered a CBC.

271
00:14:42,450 --> 00:14:44,634
Need to make sure that your
iron levels have come back up

272
00:14:44,635 --> 00:14:47,052
- and check for any possible infections.
- Okay.

273
00:14:47,053 --> 00:14:49,480
- Got any questions, honey?
- Yes. Uh...

274
00:14:49,500 --> 00:14:51,499
Visiting hours are 9:00 to 5:00, right?

275
00:14:51,500 --> 00:14:52,510
That's correct.

276
00:14:53,210 --> 00:14:54,311
[EXHALES]

277
00:14:56,104 --> 00:14:57,397
How you feeling?

278
00:14:57,420 --> 00:14:59,066
Um, you know.

279
00:14:59,420 --> 00:15:00,690
Question.

280
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:02,640
Uh, does... does someone
have to be approved

281
00:15:02,660 --> 00:15:04,028
before they can come visit?

282
00:15:04,029 --> 00:15:05,948
What... What exactly is the process?

283
00:15:05,970 --> 00:15:07,866
Is... Is it a written consent?

284
00:15:08,360 --> 00:15:10,530
Oral consent? 'Cause I'm happy to...

285
00:15:10,550 --> 00:15:11,994
I'm gonna up your meds, okay?

286
00:15:11,995 --> 00:15:15,373
No, no, no, 'cause I need to
stay awake in case he comes by.

287
00:15:16,400 --> 00:15:17,580
[DOOR OPENS]

288
00:15:17,668 --> 00:15:20,180
- Good morning.
- Oh, good morning.

289
00:15:20,220 --> 00:15:23,460
I just need to run through some of
these insurance details with you.

290
00:15:23,480 --> 00:15:24,564
Is there a chance

291
00:15:24,580 --> 00:15:27,177
that I wouldn't be getting
cell phone reception in here?

292
00:15:27,200 --> 00:15:29,346
I just wanna make sure
I'm not missing any visitors

293
00:15:29,370 --> 00:15:30,931
who try to get ahold of me.

294
00:15:30,960 --> 00:15:33,600
Can I... Can I check your phone?

295
00:15:33,684 --> 00:15:34,767
Um...

296
00:15:34,768 --> 00:15:37,396
- [CELL PHONE BUZZING]
- [GASPS, GROANS]

297
00:15:37,400 --> 00:15:40,023
[INHALES SHARPLY] Ow! [EXHALES]

298
00:15:40,050 --> 00:15:41,692
Okay. Oh.

299
00:15:42,660 --> 00:15:45,350
Hello? Dr. Ike?

300
00:15:45,780 --> 00:15:47,280
No, no. You...

301
00:15:48,300 --> 00:15:50,740
No, you h... you have
the wrong number. Yeah.

302
00:15:52,500 --> 00:15:54,240
Yeah. No. Okay.

303
00:16:03,881 --> 00:16:04,882
